ergy resources, critical providers of food production and manufacturing capacity, and drivers of national economic stability, and recognizing the work of the House of Representatives in the 119th Congress in support of those vital communities; providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 1897) to amend the Endangered Species Act of 1973 to optimize conservation through resource prioritization, incentivize wildlife conservation on private lands, provide for greater incentives to recover listed species, create greater transparency and accountability in recovering listed species, streamline the permitting process, eliminate barriers to conservation, and restore Congressional intent; and providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 5587) to amend the Geothermal Steam Act of 1970 to waive the requirement for a federal drilling permit for certain activities, to exempt certain activities from the requirements of the National Environmental Policy Act of 1969, and for other purposes :breport (to accompany H. Res. 1189). 1a[Washington, D.C.] :bU.S. Government Publishing Office,c2026.  a3 pages ;c24 cm.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier1 aReport / 119th Congress, 2d session, House of Representatives ;v119-618  a"April 20, 2026."  aReferred bill: H. Res. 1189.  aShipping list no.: 2026-0053-P.  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aDescription based on online version of print resource (GovInfo, viewed April 22, 2026); title from caption.10aUnited States.bCongress.bHousexRules and practice. 0aEnvironmental policyzUnited States. 0aEnergy conservationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aEndangered speciesxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aGeothermal resourcesxLaw and legislationzUnited S